WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.480
So it's really like I think part of the really important part of the process of package lifecycle

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:14.880
and package development is not just adding new functions, but it is equally important

00:00:14.880 --> 00:00:22.080
to remove those functions. And we know that removing functions that used to work is frustrating.

00:00:22.080 --> 00:00:27.480
And so we have developed this process, this lifecycle process of deprecation, where it

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:32.119
starts with pretty mild warnings and kind of gets progressively aggressive, more and

00:00:32.119 --> 00:00:37.720
more aggressive over time. We hope this is useful. We hope that this kind of gradually

00:00:37.720 --> 00:00:43.439
pushes you towards the golden path without like forcing you rudely when you're working

00:00:43.439 --> 00:00:49.119
on something else to urgently switch something. But at the same time, we believe that we want

00:00:49.119 --> 00:00:53.520
these functions to be better. We want these things to have a more consistent, cohesive

00:00:53.520 --> 00:00:59.959
syntax because that makes it easier for future users. And I think we're doing pretty well.

00:00:59.959 --> 00:01:04.400
We've certainly got a lot better, I think, at handling deprecations and breakages, but

00:01:04.400 --> 00:01:09.040
we're certainly still trying, still learning. And if you have any feedback, please let us know.

